nyc_bikes_extra <- nyc_bikes %>%
  mutate(year_used = year(start_time)) %>%
  mutate(month_used = month(start_time, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(date_used = as_date(start_time))
nyc_bikes_extra

2 Question 2 Summarise the number of bike hire counts by month. Make a plot of this data. *Hint: remember that to group time series (tsibble) data, you need to use index_by instead of group_by before your summarise function. What does this plot tell you about the time series? Do you think this downsampled data would be adequate to build a forecast with?

nyc_bikes_monthly <- nyc_bikes_extra %>%
  group_by_key(bike_id) %>%
  index_by(month_used) %>%
  summarise(hire_count = n()) 
nyc_bikes_monthly
ggplot(data = nyc_bikes_monthly, aes(x = month_used, y = hire_count, group = bike_id)) +
  geom_line(aes(color=bike_id))

The above shows us a seasonal trend where bikes are hired more in the summer. As this data is only for 1 year (2018), I would like to see more years before I would be comfortable plotting forecasts.

3 Question 3 Now Summarise the number of bike hire counts by date. Make a plot of this new aggregated data. What does this plot tell you about the time series? Would this data be preferrable for time series forecasting compared to the monthly data?

nyc_bikes_dates <- nyc_bikes_extra %>%
  group_by_key(bike_id) %>%
  index_by(date_used) %>%
  summarise(hire_count = n()) 
nyc_bikes_dates
ggplot(data = nyc_bikes_dates, aes(x = date_used, y = hire_count, group = bike_id)) +
  geom_line(aes(color=bike_id))

Again, this shows more of a seasonal trend to increased bike hire in the summer months. Also more data again would be ideal (this is only 1 year still) this data would be preferable for forecasting simply because there are more data points. This could perhaps be broken down further into days or weeks to help anlysis.

Question 4

Lets begin to build a model. For this, we will test the NAIVE, MEAN, and SNAIVE model.

However, the first thing youll notice when you try and build a model is that you get an error:

First, create a new tibble which uses the fill_gaps() function to fill in missing values. You havent come across this in class, but you should be able to look it up and use it using the help. Think about what value you might want to fill the missing values with. Justify your choice.

fit <- nyc_bikes_dates %>%
  model(
    snaive = SNAIVE(hire_count),
    mean_model = MEAN(hire_count),
    arima = ARIMA(hire_count)
  )

nyc_bikes_dates_full <- nyc_bikes_dates
fill_gaps(hire_counts = as.integer(median(hire_count)))

fit <- nyc_bikes_dates_full %>%
  model(
    snaive = SNAIVE(hire_count),
    mean_model = MEAN(hire_count),
    arima = ARIMA(hire_count)
  )
fit

I am using the middle here, or median because in the absence of all the data the middle values would seem to be the area with less margin for error
